WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.840
Good afternoon.

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:09.440
My talk today is about the duckplyr R package.

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:13.920
I've been working on this for the past three years together with Posit, DuckDB, and my

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:18.520
colleagues at cynkra, so thank you for this.

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:28.180
DuckDB is an embedded analytical database, SQLite for analytics.

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:33.540
Because of that, there is a variety of ways that you can package DuckDB as a command-line

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:41.779
interface, as a Python, Rust, WebAssembly, and also as an R package.

00:00:41.779 --> 00:00:46.540
I see three main reasons why you may wish to use DuckDB.

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:51.660
If your data is large, DuckDB can read straight from Parquet and from other formats.

00:00:51.660 --> 00:00:57.740
If your data analysis or data pipeline is just a little too slow, DuckDB will make it

00:00:57.740 --> 00:00:59.660
faster.

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:05.820
And then the third reason, DuckDB comes with a lot of exciting functions and data types,

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:10.339
and there are extensions that add to that.

00:01:10.339 --> 00:01:17.260
All these are valid reasons to use DuckDB as a command-line, to use the DuckDB R package.

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:24.139
Now, duckplyr, to me, this is the interface that's more native to R, and I've tried to

00:01:24.139 --> 00:01:33.099
make this more accessible so that it blends in with all the other tools in the R ecosystem.

00:01:33.099 --> 00:01:37.540
Now, looking at ways to access DuckDB from R, you could do the command-line at the bottom

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:38.540
right.

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:40.940
The more traditional way is through DBI.

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:47.820
DBI is a generic package to connect to a variety of databases, including DuckDB.

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:52.980
You would write SQL to interact through DBI or through the command-line.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:02:01.940
If you enjoy dplyr-like interfaces, as I do, you would use dbplyr that connects with DBI.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:11.380
So dbplyr translates your dplyr pipelines into SQL, runs it on the database, collects

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:14.779
the results, but only if you tell it to.

00:02:14.779 --> 00:02:21.979
So dbplyr works with lazy tables, and I forgot to mention, all of this will be available

00:02:21.979 --> 00:02:24.820
after the talk.

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:29.619
You can run the code, and the slides are on GitHub.

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:36.619
So dbplyr translates to SQL, gets the data back as a lazy table.

00:02:36.619 --> 00:02:41.300
You can collect, but you also need to collect to get this as a data frame.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:44.539
Duckplyr is similar but different in a few respects.

00:02:44.539 --> 00:02:46.979
So first, there is no SQL involved.

00:02:46.979 --> 00:02:52.259
We use a lower-level interface so that we don't have to translate to text and back from

00:02:52.259 --> 00:02:53.619
binary formats.

00:02:53.619 --> 00:02:57.639
And second, you don't need to collect.

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:04.800
So the data comes back as a true and proper data frame, and it will be materialized on

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:05.800
first access.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:08.300
I'll show this.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:14.119
This is what it looks like to access a Parquet file in SQL through the command-line.

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:19.559
You give, in the from clause, the path to the Parquet file, just as you would give a

00:03:19.559 --> 00:03:26.839
table name to your box standard database, DuckDB will read the data from the Parquet

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:28.320
file and do the operations.

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:35.080
In this case, this is a simple row count, but this can grow much more complex.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:40.559
The more traditional ways of accessing DuckDB through R look like this.

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:46.600
Typically, you would establish a DBI connection first, and then you could either for dbplyr

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:52.320
at the top right, call this function that points to the Parquet file, returns the lazy

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:59.279
table, and this then prints when you access it.

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:04.360
DBI, you write SQL the same way you would with the command-line.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:14.000
With dbplyr, this is, I believe, a little simpler, and you get back a proper data frame.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.880
Now, this is another example.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:20.119
I use a data set from Hugging Face.

00:04:20.119 --> 00:04:27.320
Instead of a file, I point it to a URL with this HF protocol specifier that points to

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:30.640
the location where the data set is.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:38.079
The same way as accessing a local Parquet file, I can run my operations, and here the

00:04:38.079 --> 00:04:43.839
explain verb will show me, before I run the operation, what is going to happen when this

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:45.880
operation is run.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:50.480
Starting with reading the Parquet file, you see we only need the two columns, so we only

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:51.640
read the two columns.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.880
That's what the Parquet file allows.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:57.040
That's what the Parquet file format allows you to do.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:02.959
Then there is this aggregation, and because the dbplyr verb sorts the result by the grouping

00:05:02.959 --> 00:05:10.959
variables, we also have this order by step at the end.

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:14.279
I have prepared a demo.

00:05:14.279 --> 00:05:17.839
So just to show you how fast this is.

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:26.880
This is over the internet, accessing this data directly from Hugging Face.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.239
I need to do two preparatory steps.

00:05:29.239 --> 00:05:34.640
The first is to get the extension that allows me the remote access.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:39.000
The second is to provide authentication, but then I'm ready to go.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:46.279
What it does is this lazy data frame, and this took no time.

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:54.200
It prints, and you can use Glimpse to get an idea what's in the data.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:06:05.559
This is 100,000 synthetic persons with demographics and textual information on their preferences.

00:06:05.559 --> 00:06:09.880
So the explain for this example is a bit different.

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:15.320
If it's the entire Parquet file, it knows the metadata, but, again, as you run queries

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:18.160
on this, you don't need to access all the columns.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:23.279
You don't need to load the data up front, which is important, I think, if you restart

00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:27.279
your R session very often.

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:28.959
This was the aggregation.

00:06:28.959 --> 00:06:32.519
No, this first was the planning aggregation.

00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:36.720
This is the computation, again, all over the internet, very fast, and what I like best

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:43.260
is you can offload this to ggplot, you can pipe this directly into ggplot, ggplot will

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:47.760
know how to handle this data, because there's nothing to know.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:52.200
This is a normal data frame for all practical purposes.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:56.519
Now, this was on the pre-aggregated data with geom col.

00:06:56.519 --> 00:07:00.959
If we try to do the same on the raw data, bam, this is what happens.

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:03.000
No, it's not going to work.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.480
The data is too large.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:11.359
This is not a bug, this is a protection mechanism I call prudence for some reason that avoids

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:13.600
frying your computer.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:19.760
So try to access a column, try to do a raw slice, no, it's not going to work.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:23.679
You can do this as soon as the data becomes small.

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:29.519
So accessing one of the columns from the results works, the data is small, and this is how

00:07:29.519 --> 00:07:32.320
ggplot got access to the data.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:40.920
So I can collect the whole data sets if I want to, but no, I'm not going to, and I'm

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:47.720
specifically proud of this, because this actually gets out cleanly.

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:55.839
So for large data, my recommendation is you can use remote access to peek into the data.

00:07:55.839 --> 00:08:02.359
This feature will avoid getting data that is too large onto your local system.

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:05.160
I forgot to mention, it would like to be everything is on the local system.

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:07.519
You don't need a big server.

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:12.640
You run everything on your workstation until it's fast.

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:17.799
If you decide to take a deeper look into the data, by all means, get it locally, because

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:22.920
this still then will be faster by an order of magnitude or two if this data fits onto

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:24.660
your disk.

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:30.260
As soon as the code is ready for production, change one line of code, the way you access

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:32.460
the data from local to remote, done.

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:38.460
It's going to work the same way.

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:41.580
Of course, analyzing large data is slow.

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:43.979
The same can be true for smaller data sets.

00:08:43.979 --> 00:08:51.460
This is a completely synthetic example, 1 million rows doing a simple summary over 40,000

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:55.059
loops, took five seconds on my machine.

00:08:55.059 --> 00:08:58.539
Imagine multiplying this by ten.

00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:04.099
Now, if you have an existing pipeline, and this is one of the strengths and one of the

00:09:04.099 --> 00:09:13.460
original purposes that that was intended for, if you have a pipeline and you just want to

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:19.700
get that a little bit faster, you have basically three strategies, you could go all in, try

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:23.500
to do end-to-end with DuckDB.

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:27.140
I think this amounts to a rewrite of the entire code.

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:29.880
The best effort mode is the default mode.

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:35.700
My recommendation would be to do a very targeted optimization of just the slow parts.

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:42.179
Now, going all in means you set an environment variable, and this will not even get to the

00:09:42.179 --> 00:09:46.940
analysis because already the generation of the data tells us, look, I don't know what

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:48.619
to do with this R norm.

00:09:48.619 --> 00:09:52.539
There is no translation for this.

00:09:52.539 --> 00:09:56.539
So even if we don't do SQL, we still need to translate, and we need to provide a translation

00:09:56.539 --> 00:10:00.460
for each and every R function that we use in the verbs.

00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:02.380
So this hasn't been done for R norm yet.

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:06.739
I'll show later how to work around it.

00:10:06.739 --> 00:10:13.859
The best effort mode, the standard mode of operation when you attach the DuckBlower package,

00:10:13.859 --> 00:10:20.380
in the beginning it will tell you, look, I am changing the way this R session works.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:24.179
Everything you do with DeepFlyer will go through DuckFlyer first.

00:10:24.179 --> 00:10:25.820
So we try with DuckFlyer.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:26.820
If it works fine.

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:31.700
If not, we offload to DeepFlyer, works the same.

00:10:31.700 --> 00:10:39.140
The generation works, and we see that the analysis, quote, unquote, now runs almost

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:41.299
in order of magnitude faster.

00:10:41.299 --> 00:10:49.859
600 milliseconds elapsed, four seconds of user time spent means all the cores of my

00:10:49.859 --> 00:10:56.140
computer have been busy computing these results.

00:10:56.140 --> 00:11:04.219
The target mode is a little more, requires a little more work.

00:11:04.219 --> 00:11:08.380
But you get better control of what happens.

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:11.140
So you don't let DuckFlyer take over.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:15.580
You undo what attaching the package does by methods restore.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:21.979
And this means that each operation will go through DeepFlyer until you tell it otherwise.

00:11:21.979 --> 00:11:28.299
And the way to tell it to go through DuckFlyer is this sduckdbtbl verb.

00:11:28.299 --> 00:11:38.020
I need collect to actually not only have a fair comparison, but to also turn this pipeline

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:42.380
back into DeepFlyer mode in this case.

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:51.299
And for a large data pipeline for one of our customers, takes 30 seconds and is used semi-interactively.

00:11:51.299 --> 00:11:53.099
So this hurts.

00:11:53.099 --> 00:11:58.380
Adding this in three crucial places in the code cuts this down to ten.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:02.419
And looking forward to do three or maybe more.

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:09.619
The slow running parts, add two lines of code, you're winning.

00:12:09.619 --> 00:12:18.260
The best effort mode, well, let me put it like this.

00:12:18.260 --> 00:12:25.780
There is a non-zero chance that the implementation will have different results with DuckFlyer

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:27.380
than with original DeepFlyer.

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:30.140
And if your pipeline implicitly relies on this.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:34.020
So I'm talking about window functions that depend on the ordering.

00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:37.460
This is a weak spot.

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:38.859
Could bring trouble.

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:45.099
So best effort mode means you please check if the results are still the same.

00:12:45.099 --> 00:12:52.299
Of course, also the targeted mode, but with the targeted mode, it is much easier to isolate.

00:12:52.299 --> 00:13:01.619
Now, we didn't have our norm, but this new DD colon syntax gives us access to all the

00:13:01.619 --> 00:13:07.419
functions in DuckDB and the extensions that are available and loaded.

00:13:07.419 --> 00:13:14.059
So just by saying DD colon colon random, we tell the system, look, there is no R function

00:13:14.059 --> 00:13:15.179
like this.

00:13:15.179 --> 00:13:18.700
Look for a DuckDB function of this name.

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:20.440
And run it for me.

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:24.520
So this will be passed through directly to DuckDB and just work.

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:28.679
We see the result as an almost uniform histogram.

00:13:28.679 --> 00:13:32.960
Now, the original code had our norm.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:40.640
This is not available in DuckDB, but there is an extension called stochastic.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:46.960
I found out by searching through a list of community extensions, and when I found stochastic,

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:50.080
it was clear that this is probably where such a function would live.

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:51.080
Bingo.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:57.440
This normal sample is available as soon as I do this load stochastic call, and I can

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:01.520
run it to get this normally distributed samples.

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:09.520
And again, piping directly to dgplot gives the plot without any extra effort.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:13.880
This DD colon colon is just an artificial syntax.

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:22.000
So if you run this code in deep R proper, this will not work today.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.880
But it is a package on GitHub that at least gives you the help pages for the function

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:29.919
that knows.

00:14:29.919 --> 00:14:36.919
So there is a help for random, and two years ago at PositConf, I was very passionate about

00:14:36.919 --> 00:14:38.679
nested data.

00:14:38.679 --> 00:14:39.679
And I still am.

00:14:39.679 --> 00:14:45.919
So these three functions are the way how you can nest and unnest data with DuckPlayer.

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:50.880
And if you're curious, this is the link to the material that gives you all the codes

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:54.400
and much more to experiment on your own.

00:14:54.400 --> 00:15:01.080
Install from Cron, run library DuckPlayer to attach the package, and maybe consider

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:08.239
methods restore, at least for new code, to get operations for large data, fast, with

00:15:08.239 --> 00:15:11.400
a lot of goodies built in.

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:12.400
Thank you.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:13.400
Thank you.

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:22.400
Plenty of time for questions.

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:23.400
All right.

00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:24.400
First question.

00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:26.539
I think somebody wants a TLDR.

00:15:26.539 --> 00:15:35.559
Why build DuckPlayer instead of using dbplayer?

00:15:35.559 --> 00:15:41.679
So again, I think this is the interface that's more native to R. Dbplayer doesn't return

00:15:41.679 --> 00:15:42.679
data frames.

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:51.200
Dbplayer returns a proxy object that you just cannot pass into ggplot unless ggplot takes

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:54.559
measures to do so, which I'm not sure it does today.

00:15:54.559 --> 00:16:00.799
And if ggplot does, many other packages will not know how to handle a lazy table from dbplayer,

00:16:00.799 --> 00:16:05.479
but they will know how to handle data frame.

00:16:05.479 --> 00:16:09.440
Thank you.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:22.960
How does DuckPlayer interact with arrow?

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:23.960
I have no idea.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:30.479
We'll save an answer for later.

00:16:30.479 --> 00:16:33.080
Can I control when prudence kicks in?

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:34.080
Yes.

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:40.440
So in all the functions that generate a lazy DuckPlayer data frame, there is a prudence

00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:46.799
argument where you can go either, well, I don't care how big the data is, to all the

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:53.400
way down to always give me an error if it cannot be run with DuckDB.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:57.640
And the middle setting, that's the default when you read from a file.

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:03.280
This will just break if the data hits a million cells by default.

00:17:03.479 --> 00:17:06.760
Okay, and I think we can have one last question.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:11.280
How does DuckPlayer avoid the user needing to call collect?

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:14.680
Once the data is small enough, does it call collect for you?

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:21.599
So no, the object is a proper data frame.

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:25.660
I don't have this here, but in the demos, there is this.

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:33.420
So this personas thing, let me open this up.

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:34.420
It has a class.

00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:38.900
The class is data frame proper with a few subclasses.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:45.660
This is essentially a list of R vectors of the same length, pretty much the same as a

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:51.020
regular data frame in memory, but each of those R vectors is an R vector.

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:56.040
This is a lazy vector technique built into our core that allows us to trigger computation

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:58.180
just when it's accessed.

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:01.380
So that's why we don't need to compute or collect.

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:02.380
Thank you.

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:03.500
Let's thank Kirill again.

